#include <iostream>
#include <string>

class GameEntity {
public:
    virtual void attack() = 0;  // Pure virtual
    // Forgot virtual destructor!
    ~GameEntity() {}
};

class Player : public GameEntity {
public:
    void attack() override {
        std::cout << "Player attacks" << std::endl;
    }
    // Forgot to implement anything else
};

int main() {
    Player p;  // ERROR! Player is still abstract!
    return 0;
}

phase2.explanation:
Player doesn't implement all pure virtual functions from GameEntity!

**What's happening:**
1. GameEntity has pure virtual `attack()`
2. Player overrides `attack()`
3. But Player is still abstract because of the missing virtual destructor

**The fix:**
```cpp
class GameEntity {
public:
    virtual void attack() = 0;
    virtual ~GameEntity() {}  // ← Add virtual destructor
};
```

**PlusPlus-chan says:**
"Abstract classes can't be instantiated. If you forget to implement any pure virtual function, or the virtual destructor, the class stays abstract."

